{
  "texts": [
    "However, scientific papers differ greatly from news articles in terms of text length, structure, terminology, and audience, making direct application of these methods to scientific paper summarization unsuitable (Gidiotis & Tsoumakas, 2020; Andrade, 2011; Oh et al., 2023).",
    "Saggion and Lapalme(2000) introduced the \"selective analysis\" method, which automatically generate informative abstracts for scientific articles by identifying their main topics.",
    "Ganesan et al. (2010) Several researchers have effectively incorporated the unique features of scientific papers, such as graphical information and chapter length, to enhance summarization.",
    "Bhatia and Mitra (2012) applied traditional machine learning methods, manually creating a set of features from scientific papers to summarize document elements.",
    "Yang et al. (2016) developed a system using a data-weighted reconstruction approach to generate extended summaries that capture the most important aspects of a scientific article."
  ]
}